ESSANDRO PEREGALLI -- tGIOVANNI RABONI -- tNELO RISI -- tTIZIANO ROSSI -- tEssays -- tPART V. The Late Sixties and Early Seventies: The Legacy of the New -- tFERNANDO BANDINI -- tGIORGIO CELLI -- tALFREDO GIULIANI -- tGIULIA NICCOLAI -- tROSSANA OMBRES -- tELIO PAGLIARANI -- tVITTORIO RETA -- tAMELIA ROSSELLI -- tROBERTO ROVERSI -- tLEONARDO SINISGALLI -- tADRIANO SPATOLA -- tANDREA ZANZOTTO -- tEssays -- tPART VI. Flash-Forward -- tEMILIO VILLA -- tEssay -- tAppendix: Giuseppe Pontiggia, An Evening of Erotic Poetry -- tBiographies -- tSources and Credits  aThose Who from Afar Look Like Flies is an anthology of poems and essays that aims to provide an organic profile of the evolution of Italian poetry after World War II. Beginning with the birth of Officina and Il Verri, and culminating with the crisis of the mid-seventies, this tome features works by such poets as Pasolini, Pagliarani, Rosselli, Sanguineti and Zanzotto, as well as such forerunners as Villa and Cacciatore. Each section of this anthology, organized chronologically, is preceded by an introductory note and documents every stylistic or substantial change in the poetics of a group or individual. For each poet, critic, and translator a short biography and bibliography is also provided.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aItalian poetryy20th centuryvTranslations into English. 0aItalian poetryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh1 aBallerini, Luigi, eeditor.1 aCavatorta, Giuseppe , eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 English